questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked
Assesses practical use of for_each with maps, resource interdependencies, and stable identities across environments. Delivers hands-on pattern candidates expect in production.

## Key Concepts
- for_each with maps provides stable keys and predictable IDs
- referencing attributes from one resource in another (subnet_id in NAT GW)
- tagging and AZ assignment per subnet
- outputs to surface IDs for downstream resources
- when to prefer for_each vs count (stable keys vs positional indexing)

## Code Example
```javascript
variable "subnets" {
  type = map(object({ cidr_block = string; az = string }))
  default = {
    az1 = { cidr_block = "10.0.1.0/24", az = "us-east-1a" },
    az2 = { cidr_block = "10.0.2.0/24", az = "us-east-1b" },
    az3 = { cidr_block = "10.0.3.0/24", az = "us-east-1c" }
  }
}

resource "aws_subnet" "private" {
  for_each = var.subnets
  vpc_id            = var.vpc_id
  cidr_block        = each.value.cidr_block
  availability_zone = each.value.az
  tags = {
    Name = "private-${each.key}"
  }
}

output "private_subnet_ids" {
  value = [for s in aws_subnet.private : s.id]
}
```

```javascript
resource "aws_nat_gateway" "ngw" {
  for_each = aws_subnet.private
  allocation_id = aws_eip.ngw[each.key].id
  subnet_id     = aws_subnet.private[each.key].id
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- When would you choose for_each over count in real projects?
- How would you migrate from count-based to for_each-based resources without breaking state?
- How would you validate AZ distribution and CIDR correctness after apply?

## Why This Is Asked

This checks practical import workflows and multi-resource management with for_each, keeping data in sync and enabling safe CI-driven promotions.

## Key Concepts

- terraform import with for_each
- map of per-bucket settings
- dynamic blocks for conditional blocks
- drift reconciliation and idempotency
- CI/CD validation and promotion

## Code Example

```javascript
variable "buckets" {
  type = map(object({
    encryption = bool
    versioning = bool
  }))
}
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "bucket" {
  for_each = var.buckets
  bucket = each.key
  acl    = "private"

  dynamic "versioning" {
    for_each = each.value.versioning ? [1] : []
    content {
      enabled = true
    }
  }

  dynamic "server_side_encryption_configuration" {
    for_each = each.value.encryption ? [1] : []
    content {
      rule {
        apply_server_side_encryption_by_default {
          sse_algorithm = "AES256"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

```javascript
terraform import 'aws_s3_bucket.bucket["team-a"]' team-a-bucket
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you handle a bucket rename in the map without recreating?
- How would you test encryption changes in CI without touching prod data?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of multi-environment deployments without code duplication using provider aliases and module iteration.

## Key Concepts
- Provider aliases
- Module instantiation with for_each
- Per-environment variable files and backends
- Terraform plan/apply targeting to avoid cross-env changes

## Code Example
```terraform
provider "aws" {
  alias  = "prod"
  region = var.prod_region
}
provider "aws" {
  alias  = "dev"
  region = var.dev_region
}
variable "prod_region" { default = "us-east-1" }
variable "dev_region"  { default = "us-west-2" }
variable "environments" {
  type = map(string)
  default = { prod = "prod", dev = "dev" }
}
module "network" {
  for_each = var.environments
  source   = "./modules/network"
  providers = { aws = aws[each.value] }
  # inputs per env
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you add a new environment without touching existing state?
- What are the trade-offs of using separate backends versus workspaces for this pattern?

questions.answer:
Configure a remote state data source in the app module to read networking outputs from S3. In app/main.tf, declare:

```hcl
data "terraform_remote_state" "networking" {
  backend = "s3"
  config = {
    bucket = "infra-state"
    key    = "networking/terraform.tfstate"
    region = "us-east-1"
  }
}

resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  subnet_id = data.terraform_remote_state.networking.outputs.public_subnet_ids[0]
  vpc_id    = data.terraform_remote_state.networking.outputs.vpc_id
  # ... additional configuration
}
```

questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked

This question tests multi-account Terraform patterns: provider aliases, cross-account data sources, and deterministic apply order.

## Key Concepts

- Aliased providers
- Cross-account data sources
- Data referencing across providers
- depends_on for ordering
- Credentials management via profiles and assume_role

## Code Example

```hcl
provider "aws" {
  alias   = "prod"
  region  = "us-east-1"
  profile = "prod"
}
provider "aws" {
  alias   = "audit"
  region  = "us-east-1"
  profile = "audit"
}

data "aws_caller_identity" "prod" {
  provider = aws.prod
}

data "aws_s3_bucket" "prod_bucket" {
  provider = aws.prod
  bucket   = "my-prod-bucket"
}

data "aws_iam_policy_document" "audit" {
  provider = aws.audit
  statement {
    actions   = ["s3:GetObject"]
    resources = ["${data.aws_s3_bucket.prod_bucket.arn}/*"]
    principals {
      type        = "AWS"
      identifiers = ["arn:aws:iam::${data.aws_caller_identity.prod.account_id}:root"]
    }
  }
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "audit_bucket" {
  provider = aws.audit
  bucket   = "audit-bucket"
}

resource "aws_iam_policy" "audit_policy" {
  provider = aws.audit
  name     = "CrossAccountGetObject"
  policy   = data.aws_iam_policy_document.audit.json
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you rotate credentials for the aliased providers safely?
- How would you test this cross-account permission in a CI workflow?
